  "prompt": "Why did Bombay turn Mumbai, Calcutta turn Kolkata?",
  "response": "The name changes from Bombay to Mumbai, Calcutta to Kolkata, and similar city name changes in India are primarily rooted in the desire to replace colonial-era names with indigenous names that reflect local languages and cultural identity. Here are more specific details:\n\n1. Mumbai (formerly Bombay):\n- \"Bombay\" was derived from the Portuguese \"Bom Bahia\" meaning \"good bay\"\n- \"Mumbai\" comes from Mumbadevi, a local Hindu goddess\n- The name change was officially implemented in 1995 by the Shiv Sena political party\n- It reflects the local Marathi language and cultural identity\n\n2. Kolkata (formerly Calcutta):\n- \"Calcutta\" was an Anglicized version of the name\n- \"Kolkata\" is closer to the Bengali pronunciation of the city's name\n- The name change was officially adopted in 2001\n- It represents a move to restore the city's original linguistic identity\n\nThese name changes were part of a broader post-colonial movement to reclaim cultural and linguistic heritage, removing vestiges of British colonial naming conventions. Similar changes occurred in other Indian cities like Chennai (formerly Madras) and Bengaluru (formerly Bangalore).",
